var cpBlogPosts=[{id:1,category:"Media Strategy",readTime:"5 min read",date:"May 2026",title:"Why Media Buying in Nigeria Is Still a Relationship Game",slug:"media-buying-nigeria-relationship-game",excerpt:"Programmatic has its place. But in Lagos, Abuja, and Port Harcourt, the deals that actually move product are still made person to person. Here is what that means for your brand strategy.",body:["The conversation around programmatic advertising has been loud for years — automated buying, real-time bidding, algorithmic targeting. And in mature markets, it works. But Nigeria is not a mature market in the programmatic sense, and treating it like one is one of the most common mistakes we see brands make.","Media in Nigeria is relationship infrastructure. The best billboard placements are not always available on a platform — they are owned by someone who knows someone, and your rate depends on the quality of your relationship with that someone. Radio sponsorships at the peak slots on stations like Wazobia FM or Beat FM are locked in through direct relationships maintained over years, not won through an automated auction.","This does not mean technology has no role. It means the technology layer sits on top of a human layer, and the human layer has to be built first. Brands that skip this and go straight to digital-only campaigns miss significant reach, particularly in markets outside Lagos Island and Victoria Island.","What this means practically: your media agency needs to have actual relationships — not just platform access — across TV, radio, OOH, and print in your target markets. If they cannot pick up the phone and call a programming director at Channels TV or a regional OOH operator in Kano, the strategy has gaps.","At Crest Point, our media buying is built on relationships cultivated over years across the country. That is not a differentiator we lead with because it sounds old-fashioned. It is simply how the market works."],tags:["Media Buying","Nigeria","Strategy"]},{id:2,category:"Brand Communications",readTime:"4 min read",date:"April 2026",title:"The Nigerian Consumer Has Changed. Most Campaign Briefs Have Not.",slug:"nigerian-consumer-evolved-campaign-briefs",excerpt:"Understanding who you are actually speaking to in 2026 is the first thing a brief should settle. Most do not.",body:["If you wrote a brief in 2019 and updated the dates, you are writing to a market that no longer exists. The Nigerian consumer — particularly in the 22 to 38 demographic — has been reshaped by inflation, the naira devaluation, increased digital literacy, and a cultural confidence that is less deferential to international brand authority than it used to be.","Premium still sells, but the value equation has tightened. Aspiration still drives purchase decisions, but it is now aspirational about specific things: experiences, time, convenience, identity — not just owning a status product. The billboard with a foreign model speaking to a generic aspiration lands differently than it did in 2018.","Brands that are winning in this environment are doing three things consistently: they are speaking in the vernacular of their actual consumer (not a fantasy of who the consumer is), they are investing in earned trust rather than just paid reach, and they are building content that has genuine shelf life rather than a 30-second interruption model.","The brief that unlocks a good campaign in this market starts with a brutally honest answer to one question: what does this person actually care about right now, in the economic and cultural moment they are living in? When a brief cannot answer that, no amount of creative execution fixes it.","This is the conversation we start with every client at Crest Point before any strategy document is written. The brief is not the start of the work. Understanding is."],tags:["Brand Strategy","Consumer Insights","Nigeria"]},{id:3,category:"Digital Marketing",readTime:"6 min read",date:"March 2026",title:"Organic Reach Is Not Dead in Nigeria. It Is Just Harder to Earn.",slug:"organic-reach-nigeria-harder-to-earn",excerpt:"The brands claiming organic is dead are usually the ones who never invested in building an audience. Here is what sustainable organic growth actually looks like.",body:["Every few months, someone publishes a piece declaring organic social media reach dead. They are usually selling paid media services. The reality is more nuanced and more useful.","Organic reach in Nigeria is not dead. It is stratified. Accounts with genuine community, consistent voice, and content that the algorithm recognises as retaining attention continue to grow. Accounts that post inconsistently, repurpose international content without local adaptation, and measure success by impressions rather than engagement are the ones that feel like organic is dead.","The platforms that matter in the Nigerian market — Instagram, X (Twitter), TikTok, and YouTube — each have distinct algorithmic logics, and each requires a different content investment. A brand trying to run one content strategy across all four will underperform on all four.","What sustainable organic looks like in practice: a content calendar built around genuine brand stories, not just product posts; a consistent posting cadence even during low-activity periods; community management that actually responds rather than broadcasting; and content that earns shares by being genuinely useful, funny, or culturally resonant — not just well-designed.","The brands with the strongest organic presence in Nigeria — across FMCG, fintech, and lifestyle — treat their social channels as media properties, not distribution channels for marketing materials. That mental shift is the thing that actually changes outcomes.","Paid amplification works best when it puts organic content that is already performing in front of more people. Paying to amplify content that organically underperforms is expensive confirmation of a content problem."],tags:["Digital Marketing","Social Media","Organic Growth"]}];

